social_posts.post_text: 🔊🔊The Amazon jungle has been called “the largest natural battlefield on earth”. Every last organism is eaten. From the insects to the godlike jaguar— or even the largest ancient trees. Life here is a countdown, a temporary moment of stasis as the jungle waits, inevitably adding all things into the rapid churning cycle.

Press your fingers into the soil and listen to the hum of the roots. Drink the rain so it becomes the rivers beneath your skin, and when you die, allow yourself to grow like braided vines into the forest so that the birds can perch on your branches as they sway in the wind. 
.

A lot of dreams came true this year. And with the incredible team at Junglekeeeprs and support from the amazing people who support us we have been able to protect thousands of acres of rainforest and MILLIONS of animal heartbeats. I got the see Africa for the first time with Vetpaw and learn a wealth of wisdom on how conservation works in another part of the world. Many of the lessons I’ve learned there can be applied to the Amazon. 

This year has also provided a striking glimpse into how people will try to take what isn’t theirs — steal, manipulate conduct the most shocking and nefarious levels of abuse. Or take generosity and use it for profit and never look back for a moment. All good things to know — hurt people really do hurt people. Bit the silver lining to walking through the snake pit — the Cypress Hill Rock Superstar blood of the arena bullshit —  is that these dark encounters only highlight even more profoundly the good people. The friends I’m blessed to have who I could trust with my life and who should trust me with theirs. And of course family. The ones you can ALWAYS rely on, rain or shine.

This year I finally found my white whale the Emerald Tree Boa. I’ve been charged by rhinos, hunted alongside a wild cheetah, explored parts of the Amazon no one has seen, spoke at the United Nations and had a blast with some amazing people. Thank you for following along — there are big things coming, and wild new adventures in the works 🦋

The Queen of the Amazon. The anaconda. Most of us don’t think of snakes as 20 feet long with heads the size of a Rottweiler. But this is one of the legendary animals that haunts the deep swamps of the greatest jungle on earth. From a little 2 ft hopeless neonate this snake has spent decades swimming through the soupy swamps of the jungle to become a dragon. There are scars on her skin, stories in he scales, and she is the apex. The matriarchal riparian zenith of this ecosystem and one of the most mind-blowing creatures on this earth. Are there larger out there? Certainly. I’ve seen them. But she is a monster, a force of nature, a thing of mythic proportions and it is one of the great privileges of my life that I got to spend these moments with her.

It doesn’t seem real. That such a sanctuary could exist on earth. Such incredible creatures. Protected by the efforts of such committed people. The antithesis to the agony of extinction — hope.

Meanwhile in the Amazon leaf cutter ants are harvesting flowers 🌺 These incredible ants have the distinction of being the primary consumer of vegetation in the Amazon rainforests, where their actions remove 15–17% of leaf production. Leaf-cutter ants live in massive colonies – sometimes reaching three million – and can extend deep under ground where they build ventilation tunnels, reproduction chambers, farms, all forming gigantic hills for their homes.

Human perception is a funny thing. Out of sight out of mind. Each dry season I watch more of the Amazon destroyed, and see the flurry of posts and articles, then for the rest of the year the intensity dies down. But if we are going to protect this place we need to be always working.

Someone recently asked me about all the destruction I’ve seen. Years and years of watching vibrant green rainforest turned to ashes. Animals and ancient trees on fire. Species we will never know the names of gone up in smoke. My life is filled with moments like this photo, from the killing fields of Amazonia, where we are literally incinerating our most precious ecosystems. I brushed off the question because it was too monstrous of a topic to handle in polite conversation. More recently a television producer suggested that I should stay away from showing the “harsh stuff” and stick to “more positive content” if I wanted to make a difference for wildlife. It made me think of the strange path I’ve chosen, and the hundreds of messages I get from kids asking “how do I get your job?”. And that old Bukowski poem where he keeps saying: Don’t do it.

These artifacts are a quiet collection of eccentric travelers who have found home within the pages. Feathers are ragged relics of something magnificent, once brilliantly alive, lofted high on the thermals or flitted through the forest, much like the faded graphite and sloppy scribbled ink. Fragments of mundane moments cooking in the kitchen with the warm music and rich smell of garlic. The wise words of those who are no longer here. Then there are the heavyweights—the massive mesmeric moments that shatter whatever I dared to dream possible and redefined the meaning of reality. Walking with giants. The waves that eclipsed the sun. The cold darkness that could swallow it all. They say success isn’t owned it’s leased, and the rent is due every day. In the jungle it’s the same for survival. And in conservation it’s never ending — if you want to protect an ecosystem the victories are temporary and the losses are final. And so we keep telling stories, keep patrolling, keep rallying support from people around the globe—keep tirelessly guarding what is threatened. And often what is required is the blunt simplicity of moving forward — which in the jungle is never an easy task. Motors break. Food goes bad. Whatever the problem of the day is, we shoulder it, share it, and keep walking.

We were good friends. Though most of our time was antagonistic in nature. He would demand bananas, and if I didn’t give them, then he’d crush my tripod. Or threaten to knock over a jeep (no l’m not kidding). He could read what I cared about the most, and which things were expensive. The game was simple: ‘give me bananas or I’ll break your things’. He is an antagonizer, a giant selfish pain in the ass - and he loves the reaction as much as the payoff. Pretty much my spirit animal. So what was interesting to me were the times he knew I had nothing to give him, when I’d just be sitting with my notebook, drinking tea, and writing. He didn’t really know what to make of it. As time passed he’d try and take my notebook with his trunk. When I yelled at him and he turned and pushed me over with his foot. I yelled at him louder and he got upset and went to a tree where he was rubbing his eye against the bark. Then I felt bad. So I’d put down what I was doing and go rub his eyes with flat palms. He loved that. All the knocking things over, my crushed sunglasses - it was all just an attempt at communication. His wrinkled eyes closed under my palms as I rubbed. When I finished he searched my shoes and pockets and hair with his trunk. Then we just were standing there in the forest forehead to forehead - smiling. Playing. Falling asleep.

She clung to her mother as they swung through the trees. Through the emerald canopy of orchids and vines. She clung through her mother when the gun fired and they fell. Since then she’s been living in the mining camp with the dogs and chickens. At night she sleeps alone in the dark, in the dirt, under the floor. All alone. // I went under the floorboards at 6pm with a flashlight to see if she was there. She was curled up like an orphan, her eyes bleary in the beam of my headlamp. I held her for a bit and felt sad. Then I let her crawl back into the darkness so I could go do human things: carry gear, eat dinner, shower. // Later at 9pm that night she came into the sphere of the candle light – I hadn’t seen her in hours. She looked like a starving shadow with sparkling eyes. She came slowly, talking nervously in the staccato of her kind, and I spoke back to her. We conversed in spider monkey speak for a while and slowly she came closer. She was visibly terrified of the dogs and the miner’s as they walked around. But she kept coming closer. I was almost certain of why, but was unwilling to believe what I knew. I stayed very still and told her it was ok. Then she climbed up my leg, up my arm, and curled her tail around my neck. She stayed there for the next fourteen hours. In my bed, under the covers When I slept on my back, she was on my stomach. When I went to my stomach she moved to my back (where she also took a healthy dump). The next morning she was snoring on my shoulder, tail wrapped around my neck. We hiked in the forest together. // This little monkey was so incredibly starved for contact, for love, that after tasting it briefly in the afternoon, came back at night and risked darkness, dogs, and miners to come over to get more. We think of ourselves as superior, but they need, just as badly as we do, to be loved. The sadness in her eyes was devastating. When I finally had to leave, she screamed like I was peeling her skin off. ..This monkey is actually part of a very inspiring story. But that’s for later. Right now I still very much feel the pain in this little animal.

Around 1900 there were over 100,000 tigers on earth. Today we have roughly 4,000 remaining in the wild. Habitat destruction, hunting, and all out extermination have drastically reduced the numbers of these powerful predators. It is a rare and deeply profound privilege to see one walk the wild.
It’s time. Back to Amazonia. And you’re coming with me.

“It is curious that the Amazon, so large in our minds, is actually quite small. From far above on a clear day the God’s-eye view from a plane-the jungle looks like moss across an endless field, Even the clouds are far below, barely over the canopy, like bits of cotton blown across some lawn—or like mothers doting over the greenery, carefully watering the jungle from above. From so high up, the great jungle can be seen for what it really is: a very delicate collection of life on the smooth face of a planet. The greatest of its creatures become microbes, the great trees are reduced to lichen even the bipedal primates that are so clever seem small and insignificant, save for the great scars they cut into the green. Cleverness is evident in this grand exploitation, but it will take a different kind of intelligence to preserve the whole and heal the wounds.
And so the question becomes whether this one species can rise from cleverness to actual intelligence; to evolve from being a blight on the great basin to become instead the greatest of its stewards. But that remains to be seen.

Thankfully there are still vast stretches where the green is unbroken and the canopy extends to the horizon.”

—Mother of God: An Extraordinary Journey into the Uncharted Tributaries of the Western Amazon

These awesome arthropods also known as whip spiders or tailless whip scorpions (not to be confused with whip scorpions or vinegaroons that belong to the related order Thelyphonida). The name “amblypygid” means “blunt tail”, a reference to a lack of the flagellum that is otherwise seen in whip scorpions. Amblypygids possess no silk glands or venomous fangs. It is a privilege to be able to witness this vast wisdom of the forest held by these people even today. As deforestation sweeps the Amazon, and roads bring rapid change, the deep knowledge of Amazonian botanical medicine is at tenuous point in history where we have a great wealth of hard-won ancient knowledge that very much needs to be studied, celebrated, and passed on. Because as Plotkin aptly notes, “Every time a shaman dies, it is as if a library burned down.”

When Junglekeepers first began collaborating with Age of Union to protect the Las Piedras River in the Madre de Dios region of Peru, their team was hard at work building their ranger program, researching local wildlife, and establishing the area as a conservation corridor.

With these goals in mind, Junglekeepers also recognized an important opportunity: supporting existing local conservation efforts.

By focusing on established initiatives led by communities in the Madre de Dios region, Junglekeepers and Age of Union can provide crucial financial and tactical support to locally-run projects.

As part of our program to support these initiatives, Junglekeepers has teamed up with three community-based conservation projects actively working on the ground to conserve the Madre de Dios region:

🐒 Amazon Shelter (@amazonshelter), a wildlife rehabilitation centre dedicated to protecting wounded and orphaned animals in the Amazon.

🌴 ARBIO (@arbioperu), a women-led, non-profit organization whose dedicated team of rangers protects ancient forest from logging in the Las Piedras basin.

🥭 Cocinando Y Conservando (@cocinando_conservando), an initiative founded by Junglekeepers President @royriquelmer that promotes health, wellness, and connection to the land for the people of Madre de Dios through cooking with local, sustainable ingredients.

Learn how these dedicated community-based initiatives are preserving the Amazon Rainforest in our latest article by @junglekeepers Founder @paulrosolie. Link in bio. 🔗

Wills Earth Oceania Champion @paulrosolie is a naturalist, explorer, author, and award winning wildlife filmmaker. His short film An Unseen World won the @unitednations Forum on Forests 2013 short films award, and has been described as ‘nature filmmaking at its most raw and innovative”.

Specializing in tropical rain forests, his work has taken him to place like Borneo, India, Brazil, and Peru. In the Amazon he has traveled with poachers into deep jungle to document the black market trade in endangered species, researched giant anacondas, raised an orphaned giant anteater by hand, and explored a previously undocumented ecosystem that has come to be called the ‘floating forest’. He spends extended periods in solitude, paddling his raft in remote corners of the jungle, filming, writing, and observing wildlife.

His book Mother of God has gained the praise of environmentalists and adventurers such as Jane Goodall, Bear Grylls, and Bill McKibben who have called the book a “gripping”, “awe inspiring”, “rousing tale”, “with a great and enduring point”.

Founder of @junglekeepers and presenting for the second time in as many years st the @worldclimatefoundation, Rosolie’s work is underpinned by the generous support of @ageofunion and embraced by world leaders and influencers including most recently the @joerogan podcast.

This used to be the Amazon Rainforest. I am on a mission to document the unseen destruction. “For a long moment I’m just tripping over charred trees and squinting against the black ashes that swirl through the smoke-choked air. I raise my camera only to realize that it has stopped working. It’s simply too hot. The heat is murderous. A sudden explosion and I cover my head with my arms. I duck, but don’t go down fully (because if I do I’ll be burned alive). I need to get out of there. A second blast, as boiling sap explodes out of an ancient tree, sending wood shards ripping through the air. The sixty-foot wall of flames roars through the forest as branches flail and leaves are swept upwards with the black glut of smoke that is now blotting out the sun. As my vision blurs and my lungs burn, I run through the ash, suddenly unsure of how to escape the blackened hellscape I am in.”

They say you’re born alone and you die alone.

People whose lives and yours will become braided in the most fascinating ways. To have real friends. Those ride-or-die friends, true-to-the-bone good people—the family. The life-ers... At night we see the sky in its full aspect, a brilliance and millions-multitude of stars that seems un-believable because we have had our perceptions dimmed for so long. The morning comes like something from Joseph Conrad's basement tapes. Light creeps over the canopy well before the sun, the world growing a little less black, to purple to blue, the stars gently fading as the dawn chorus rises from the jungle. Every animal is waking and stretching, shaking the dew from their feathers and scales and fur. When the sun comes up in the east it is a miracle and the jungle becomes a celebration of the new day as the air fills with clouds and rushing birds, and the treetops crash with the moving troops of monkeys. It seems unbelievable, surreal even, to be in such a reality, surrounded by such life. Then it all circles back and you realize...

Traveling through the Madre de Dios, I had seen forest devastated by logging and hunting as well as places degraded by gold mining and its long-lived mercury contamination. But, in contrast, I had also seen the most secluded and pristine wilderness imaginable and the resulting riot of wildlife. Again and again the inverse rule held: the farther from humans you travel, the more animals you see. Now, traveling upriver on a boat for days I was considerably farther from civilization than I had ever been.

With each bend in the river, the beaches were more crowded with tracks evidencing the visits of large animals, the hulks of basking caiman, and endless flocks of birds. Likewise, tree branches exploded with life. It was a celebration of human absence.

—Excerpts from my first book: Mother of God: An extraordinary journey into the Uncharted Tributaries of the Western Amazon

The good news is that deforestation in the Brazilian Amazon is down 66% compared to last year. This seems to be in relation to the administration change in Brazil’s president. It’s great news. But while Brazil holds more of the Amazon than any other country, the worlds greatest rainforest has significant portions in many other countries. Most notably Peru. On the ground here. Nothing has changed. It’s the dry season, and humans are cutting ancient forest and burning it to make farmland. We are losing vital ecosystems and endangered species so that illegal farms can be created to grow fucking papayas. We are smarter than this. There is a better way. 

@junglekeepers is working with indigenous leaders to stop the destruction of our primary forest. This work is made possible by our major funders @daxdasilva @ageofunion — and by the hundreds of people who donate at www.junglekeepers.org

My shirt was melting to my skin. The cameras and phones couldn’t handle the heat. We live in a world where information gets politicized. Whether or not you think something happened or is happening in many cases, becomes a subject for debate or belief. But the truth is out there. The fact is we are losing ancient forest, and the millions of heartbeats who live inside of it. The truth is these fires are not natural. We can fix this. We can stop this. We can protect the ancient rainforest. And that is why every year I will be there. Every year I will watch the forest I love burn. Until the world notices and it stops.

Less than 3% of the sunlight that falls on the Amazon Rainforest actually makes it through the leaves and vines and branches of the canopy, down through the understory and the bromeliads, to touch the forest floor. The beams that do reach the forest floor are flecked and scattered, dappled sunlight traces across the leafy floor, blooming and eclipsing in moments here and there. 

Most of the humans I see are always hustling through a forest. They are lifting cameras or clipboards, checking their phones, urgently striding to one place or another. But if you sit out in the forest, you realize a few things. One is that you need to protect yourself from mosquitoes. The next is that after twenty minutes the forest settles around you. The birds decide you have shown you are capable of peace and are not, at least for now, worthy of their alarm calls. There's a saying out there about how if you want to be the best, you have to be willing to be willing to do things other people simply aren't willing to do. Well the same goes for if you want to see incredible things in the wild. Sitting alone silently, in the jungle, you are exposed to something very few people experience, and in doing so get to see things in a way and with a perspective that is quite incredible.

I have found lizards and snakes in the pools of sunlight. Sometimes it's a massive yellow-tailed cribo (snake) in a bed of leaves. Or a golden giant tegu (lizard) smiling in the warm sun. Sometimes the blue morphos (butterflies) decide to show off and do magic, and blast you with a ray of paralyzing blue. This little metalmark butterfly (mantinea, castalia, or fulvimargo?) held me transfixed for longer than I'll admit. And I stalked it, while it was enjoying the sun, until I was inches away from it, lying on my stomach, completely amazed at every detail.

Think the lapwings ever slip? ;) Riverside in the morning is magic — pied lapwings, caiman, and hundreds of other species. We often do riparian transects and come back with over 70 species recorded for just two hours of survey. It’s simply stunning how wild this place is. And we are already missing a few species, like black caiman and anacondas. So there is restoration work to be done here but currently there are so many incredible species the call this river home!

Every day we see something wondrous and new. The stunning sunrise. A caiman with butterflies all over her face. A jaguar swimming across the current. This river is magic. It is the bedrock in our brains, the subtext of or thoughts and beliefs. Seventeen years this beautiful place has been home.

The emerald stained glass ceilings of the green cathedral — the jungle is so tall and complex that I always a feel minuscule, insignificant. It’s a calm morning.

We ran low on food last week. Everyone at camp was starting to go crazy because all we had been eating was rice. The eggs were gone. We had no cheese or meat. It felt like in weeks. We didn’t even really have any fruit. And so Victor led the expedition up river. He said we had to hunt hungry. That’s the truest way. So we brought nothing to eat for dinner or for breakfast. The plan was that we would camp on the beach and then wake up at dawn and float down the river. It’s a privilege to learn the indigenous ways. It was our best shot for actually getting some thing that could help us keep everyone healthy for the following days. 

Inevitably there’s gonna be somebody who is upset that I hit the fish with a hammer while smiling. But trust me, when it really matters, after hours and hours of trying with no luck, it’s a wonderful feeling being able to finally achieve success. And the only way to safely keep these fish in the boat, without them, flopping out, is to shut them off quick. And the best way to do that is with the hammer. It’s much more humane for the fish.

The was a really special day. And with three of these giant fish. We were able to feed everyone at camp for many days.

A young cheetah stares back at me. Cheetah are gorgeous, slender and majestic. There’s no other cat like them. In 1970, the cheetah population hovered at 25,000; now we’re down to less than 6,000 or 10% from the 1900s. Like all predators in the modern world, Farmers consider them a nuisance to livestock and kill then preventatively. Then of course there is the fact that as humans we continue encroaching on their habitat.

Today we feast! There’s nothing like watching the concentration and skill of the cheetahs at @buffalokloof — a mother and her cubs out in the grass. Each day if they want to eat she has to run fast, hard, smart, and risk it all. I’ve seen some amazing chases. She always comes through for her cubs. Even more amazing is watching as they grow, and she begins to teach them in the most ingenious ways, how to begin to hunt for themselves. It always feels good to see them happy, feasting and safe.

They need us. It’s one thing that I have realized beyond all doubt: that animals feel more deeply than our capacity to comprehend. When the jungle is destroyed, their world is gone, and when their mother is gone, there is no one to love and defend them. They will starve or be eaten. More than once I’ve felt the desperate warmth of a traumatized little primate wrap around my neck, only to moments later hear the subtle snoring of one that has been through much and knows, at last, that they are safe.

If diversity is a source of wonder, its opposite - the ubiquitous condensation to some blandly amorphous and singularly generic modern culture that takes for granted an impoverished environment - is a source of dismay. There is, indeed, a fire burning over the earth, taking with it plants and animals, cultures, languages, ancient skills and visionary wisdom. Quelling this flame, and re-inventing the poetry of diversity is perhaps the most important challenge of our times.

The earth was smoking, so we had to walk carefully. Blackened trees were still glowing on the ashy ground, the tropical sun blindingly hot. Dax and I had walked through towering ancient forest to reach this spot, and so the contrast was shocking: what had once been dark green, jungle-shaded, moist, and lush with life was now obliterated to scorched earth. The trees lay blackened and smouldering. Wildlife was gone. As we walked, we could hear the snap and pop of fire but little else. Everything had been destroyed. 

You can read the full article on Age of Union’s website— but I’ll tell you here: this story taught me something. Seeing the regrowth taught me something. It reaffirmed that if we were not doing this work, this forest would certainly be destroyed. It also kindled what I had always hoped: if we can protect this ancient ecosystem, the jungle can endure some scars. We may have lost some crucial acres, but because we are covering most of the surrounding habitat, the forest will continue the endless march of life, and the churning speciation will continue for uninhibited millennia. And long after we are all gone, a great and ancient basin of life will continue to exist in an ever-changing world. 

Thank you @daxdasilva and @ageofunion for making this crucial work possible!

“Our wildest dreams never included what we are doing now,” says conservationist Paul Rosolie in a new podcast interview with Mongabay. What began as a grassroots initiative of his and partner Juan Julio Durand, Junglekeepers has evolved into a conservation nonprofit now protecting 55,000 acres (22,258 hectares) of rainforest in the Las Piedras corridor of the Madre de Dios region of Peru. Like many similar areas, this portion of the Amazon can be dangerous for environmental defenders: “[I]t’s the middle of the Amazon. We’re past where law enforcement goes,” Rosolie says.

In this podcast conversation, Rosolie speaks with Mongabay about the success of his nonprofit and that of Tamandua Expeditions, an ecotourism service providing conservation-focused travel. He also shares what messages resonate with audiences, how he’s worked with local and Indigenous communities to recruit loggers to become conservation rangers, and what he thinks conservation organizations can do to increase their impact.

The talons on this sub-adult Harpy Eagle are no joke. Harpy’s are impressive in size (2m wingspan!) and have been known to snatch monkeys and sloths and just about anything else they want off the branches of the rainforest. They eat 2lb or about a kilogram of meat per day. You can find a harpy nest because there’s often a pile of bones under it. These are savage apex predators and an unquestionable indicator species: where there are harpy’s, the jungle is healthy.

Huge news! After 26 years of fighting for their rights the community of Puerto Nuevo was unable to obtain titled land from the government. Things weren’t moving, the government process was stuck, and finances to get from their remote community to the offices in the nearest city were running out. Over the last year Junglekeepers has been proudly supporting this historic indigenous community and we are so excited to share this massive success. Can you believe it? Twenty-six YEARS of fighting for their home to be recognized and safe. The Community of Puerto Nuevo now is a government recognized indigenous community and the future for both the people and the river is bright! 

This is huge news! We’ve always believed in biocentric conservation—that humans, animals, rivers are all braided and essential parts of a landscape. Thanks to the incredible team at Junglekeepers especially @royriquelmer and @dinatsouluhas and Juan Julio Durand and the dynamic and unwavering support of @daxdasilva and @ageofunion we are actually changing the narrative!

The pointy, backward-facing papillae are to help it eat a large number of the slippery jellyfish by preventing them from escaping by floating out the back of its mouth.
